description.narrative:
The Asian Development Bank (ADB), together with its development donors - the Government of Sweden, Nordic Development Fund, and the Multi-Donor Trust Fund under the Water Financing Partnership Facility - provided a regional technical assistance (TA) to support the Greater Mekong Subregion (GMS) in implementing Core Agriculture Support Programme Phase 2 (CASP2). Sida channeled 53 MSEK to ADB to support this TA for the period of October 2012 to June 2018.
The program has accomplished a number of the accomplishments despite challenges met during the implementation. The following are major milestones achieved:
- Endorsement of a participatory GMS Strategy for Promoting Safe and Environment Friendly Agro-Based Value Chains in the Greater Mekong Subregion and Siem Reap Action Plan, 2018-2022 (GMS SASRAP) by the GMS Agriculture Ministers;
- Conduct of the second GMS Agriculture Minister's Meeting after a decade;
- Conduct of a GMS-themed trade fair in the THAIFEX;
- Collaboration between the Working Group on Agriculture (WGA) and the Food Industry Asia (FIA, an association comprising a large number of global agribusiness as members) with two concrete actions co-financed by the TA and the FIA members; 
- Development of knowledge products, e.g. Policies for High Quality, Safe and Sustainable Food Supply in the GMS, Value Chain Studies, Gender Dimension in Low-Input Agriculture Value Chains in the GMS;  
- Strengthened GMS WGA initiating inter-sector and multi-stakeholder links and during the next five years of CASP. 
Gender equality has been integrated throughout the programme, and some results achieved are: i) increase rate of participation of women in sub-project activities (e.g. 55% in Myanmar); ii) 30% of the total trained farmers have adopted Green Water Management and Climate-Friendly Agriculture (CFA) in Vietnam, of whom 35% were women. The sub-projects have increased women's income due to reduced costs in input usage, and increased productivity and farming efficiency. To strengthen gender aspects, a study on Gender Dimension in Low-Input Agriculture Value Chains in the GMS was completed. It aims to understand the gender dimensions in low-input agriculture value chains in GMS economics and refine the economic and social impacts of their engagement in these economic activities.
